<section xml:id="sec-what-is-de" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>What is a Differential Equation?</title>

  <p>
    Derivatives are used to model changing situations! And things are changing all around us!
  </p>

  <example xml:id="ex-setup-population-de">
    <title>Setting Up a Differential Equation</title>
    <p>
      Come up with an equation that models the following situation: <em>The rate of change of a population <m>P(t)</m> (where <m>t</m> is time in years) is proportional to the current population. The constant of proportionality is 3.</em>
    </p>
    <hint>
      <p>
        The rate of change of <m>P</m> is the derivative with respect to time, which is <m>\frac{dP}{dt}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        "The rate of change of <m>P(t)</m> is..." translates to <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = \ldots</m> What can you put on the right-hand side of the equation to represent that it is proportional to the current population, where the constant of proportionality is 3?
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The answer is <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>. The left-hand side <m>\frac{dP}{dt}</m> denotes <em>the rate of change of the population</em>. The right-hand side, <m>3P</m>, expresses a quantity that is proportional to <m>P</m>, with a proportionality constant of 3.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <p>
    In the previous example, you just set up a <em>differential equation</em>. We often want to take this a step further and find a solution. In this case, that would be a population function <m>P(t)</m> that satisfies the conditions of the previous example. But first, let's warm up with a simpler question!
  </p>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-mc-solve-dPdt-P">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Which of the following is a solution to <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = P</m>?
      </p>
        <p>
        Notice this says the derivative of <m>P(t)</m> is itself. What famous 
        function has this property?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p><m>P(t) = e^t</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Correct! The derivative of <m>e^t</m> is itself, so <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = e^t = P</m>. <m>\checkmark</m>
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p><m>P(t) = t^2</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not quite — the derivative of <m>t^2</m> is <m>2t</m>, not <m>t^2</m> itself.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p><m>P(t) = \sin(t)</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not quite — the derivative of <m>\sin(t)</m> is <m>\cos(t)</m>, not <m>\sin(t)</m>.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p><m>P(t) = t</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not quite — the derivative of <m>t</m> is <m>1</m>, not <m>t</m> itself.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    Now let's try the original question. If it feels tricky, that's okay, we will learn systematic methods for solving ODEs later in the course. For now, it's fun to play around on your own for a minute before revealing the solution!
  </p>

  <example xml:id="ex-solve-population-de">
    <title>Solving a Differential Equation</title>
    <p>
      Can you think of a function <m>P(t)</m> that solves <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>?
    </p>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Recall from the previous checkpoint that <m>P(t) = e^t</m> solves <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = P</m>. How can we modify this function to solve <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>? Think about the chain rule!
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
        <p>
          Let's check <m>P(t) = e^{3t}</m>. By the chain rule:
          <me>\frac{d}{dt}e^{3t} = 3\underbrace{e^{3t}}_{=\,P} = 3P.</me>
          So <m>P(t) = e^{3t}</m> solves <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>!
        </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <p>
    This is not the only solution to <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>. Can you think of any others? We will reveal the answer on the next page!
  </p>

  <p>
    The population example illustrates a key idea: when modelling situations that change over time, we naturally arrive at equations involving derivatives. This is the essence of a differential equation, which we now define formally.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-differential-equation">
    <title>Differential Equation</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>differential equation</term> is an equation involving a function <m>y(x)</m>, its derivatives <m>y', y'', y''', \ldots</m>, and an independent variable <m>x</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <term>order</term> of a differential equation is the highest derivative appearing.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    A differential equation involving only derivatives with respect to one variable (as opposed to partial derivatives) is called an <term>ordinary differential equation (ODE)</term>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Here are three examples of ODEs, along with their orders:
    <md>
      <mrow>\frac{dP}{dt} \amp= 3P \quad \leadsto \text{1st order}</mrow>
      <mrow>\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} + x^2 \amp= \frac{dy}{dx} e^x \quad \leadsto \text{2nd order}</mrow>
      <mrow>y''' + y''y + \sin(y') \amp= x \quad \leadsto \text{3rd order}</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>

  <remark xml:id="rem-notation">
    <title>Notation</title>
    <p>
      We adopt both the prime notation <m>y'</m> and Leibniz notation <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m> to denote the derivative of <m>y</m> with respect to <m>t</m>. These are equivalent and will be used interchangeably throughout.
    </p>
    <p>
      In <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>, <m>t</m> is the <em>independent variable</em> and <m>P</m> is the <em>dependent variable</em>. The actual letters we use for the variables will vary. In the last example, <m>y''' + y''y + \sin(y') = x</m>,
       it is implied that <m>y</m> is the dependent variable and <m>x</m> is the independent variable.
    </p>
  </remark>

